Fig. 2
a shows transition electron microscopy (TEM) image of the prepared CQDs dispersed in distilled water. The well-dispersed Pd-NPs supported on CQDs can be observed from the TEM image has been shown in Fig. 2b. As it is observed, the average size of the particles increases due to the decoration of Pd-NPs on RCQDs. [54–57] Also, the SEM images were used to confirm the distribution of Pd- NPs on CQDs both deposited on GCE (Fig. 3
).

For more understanding about the kinetic and mechanism of desired reaction, investigation of temperature effect and subsequently calculation of activation energy, Ea
                        , can be helpful. For this purpose, the LSV voltammograms were recorded at temperatures from 293 to 323 K for both Pd-NPs/GCE and Pd-NPs/RCQD/GCE (Fig. 9
                        ).

The concentration of methanol also affects kinetics and electrochemical features of the reaction that has been shown in Fig. 11
                        . According to Fig. 11, peak current density, ip, of MOR raises up as the concentration of methanol is increased for both Pd-NPs/GCE and Pd-NPs/RCQD/GCE. The ratio of the forward anodic peak current density (If
                        ) to the reverse anodic peak current density (Ib
                        ) is utilized to illustrate the tolerance of catalyst to the intermediate carbonaceous species. Accordingly increases of the If/Ib
                         by methanol concentration for Pd-NPs/RCQDs/GCE indicates the completeness of methanol oxidation at forward scan that can be due to the improved dispersion of nanoparticles because of the presence of CQDs. While by increases of methanol concentration on Pd-NPs/GCE this ratio decreases that can be due to the significant poisoning of the electrode with intermediates. [81] So, the incorporation of RCQDs, with several oxygenated functional groups leads to the oxidation and facilitated desorption of adsorbed intermediates [82].
